comment.narrative:
The Make Way programme is using the following definition of ‘becoming more inclusive’: 

- integrate intersectional advocacy approaches in our work 
- represent more marginalised youth with compounded vulnerabilities 
- have the knowledge, capacity, support and networks to self-organise and help scale-up intersectionality advocacy approaches to SRHR 

Taking this definition into account, implementation contexts are measuring how their collaborating partners will have become more inclusive. They will do this by assessing how an intersectional lens have been integrated in evidence building and/or programming; how collaborating partners have shaped their advocacy agenda on intersectional SRHR for minoritised youth; and how the action plans based on the self-assessments have been implemented. 

Our toolkit for intersectional SRHR lobby and advocacy is being developed to play a key role in supporting our collaborating partners to become more inclusive, and having strengthened capacity to undertake intersectional SRHR L&A. It contains materials that cover a range of topics, including: 

- understanding intersectionality; 
- qualitative research and SRHR issues analysis;  
- quantitative research;  
- policy analysis;  
- lobby, advocacy and communications;  
- and youth engagement. 

We will organise introduction sessions and webinars to support understanding of the tools/materials in the toolkit. Moreover, as consortium we are organising awareness raising sessions and trainings with and for consortium partners and collaborating partners on intersectionality, inclusion, disability, social accountability, religion and global health advocacy (focused on health systems strengthening).

