In 2021 we undertook a capacity assessment of intersectional lobby and advocacy for SRHR among our CPs. We looked at various aspects of the ability to implement intersectional SRHR lobby and advocacy:

- selection and analysis of SRHR issues;
- stakeholder mapping;
- movement-building and coalition-building;
- developing communication and media strategies;
- developing advocacy goals and plans;
- evaluating lobby and advocacy plans

The assessment showed the following results:

- For five of the six implementation contexts, the CPs gave the highest average scores to Movement and Coalition-building, which indicates that most capacity is available in this area of the advocacy cycle. On two occasions, the highest average score was given to Implement lobby & advocacy Plans and Develop Advocacy Plan.
- In three contexts, the CPs gave the lowest average scores to Develop Communications & Media Strategy. In two contexts, the lowest average scores were given to Development of Advocacy Goals and in one context Analysis of Issues received the lowest score.
- The total scores (across the seven lobby & advocacy performance areas) for each CP ranged significantly within each of the contexts. This suggests that capacity for undertaking intersectional SRHR advocacy is high among some of our CPs and considerably lower among others.

In total with the Make Way programme, we will influence 43 strategic documents, including laws, government policies, by-laws and international agreements. Details about which strategic documents will be targeted and what the specific desired changes are, will be specified in the context-specific baseline and target information.

Overarchingly, the desired changes for which we will advocate relate to the following overarching topics:

· the availability, accessibility, acceptability and quality (AAAQ) of SRH services;

· the availability and distribution of skilled health workers; 

· the allocation or raising of funding for the AAAQ of SRH services for all (including marginalised youth);

· strengthening of public health systems;

· collaboration and harmonisation between relevant ministries and across policies (at national and/or global levels);

· intersectionality gaps in policies/strategic documents, and the intersectional assessment of donors’ programmes;

· comprehensive sexuality education (CSE);

· the wording of regional documents in relation to ‘rights’ and the SRHR of minoritised groups. 

· financing gaps in policy implementation;

· funding of health insurance;

· the training of duty-bearers on SRHR;

· meaningful youth participation in policy review and implementation;

· the SRHR needs of marginalised youth, incl. access to SRHR information; 

· and, data on and protection against gender-based violence.

